01:16:15.048 --> 01:16:18.095
Because we all have truths in
our lives that we avoid hearing.

1222
01:16:18.138 --> 01:16:19.662
that we don't want to confront

1223
01:16:19.705 --> 01:16:21.707
or don't want to admit
to ourselves.

1224
01:16:21.751 --> 01:16:24.057
Yet. it's by confronting
or admitting them

1225
01:16:24.101 --> 01:16:27.583
that we can actually
open the way to become better.

1226
01:16:34.024 --> 01:16:35.939
A lot of people
don't like hearing this.

1227
01:16:35.982 --> 01:16:39.290
Like. we like to hear that our
problems can be solved forever.

1228
01:16:39.333 --> 01:16:44.382
we like to hear that there's
some formula to be happy.

1229
01:16:44.425 --> 01:16:46.427
live happily ever after.

1230
01:16:46.471 --> 01:16:50.388
But I'm sorry.
but Disappointment Panda says.

1231
01:16:50.431 --> 01:16:54.305
"No. there's not.
This is simply how life is."

1232
01:16:54.348 --> 01:16:57.090
And so if we're forced
to have problems.

1233
01:16:57.134 --> 01:16:59.353
then we might as well
find the problems

1234
01:16:59.397 --> 01:17:00.964
that we enjoy having in life.

1235
01:17:01.007 --> 01:17:03.183
You know. when everybody
hears this idea

1236
01:17:03.227 --> 01:17:04.881
of. like. not giving a fuck.

1237
01:17:04.924 --> 01:17:08.406
you kind of imagine this. like.
cool dude kicking back. like.

1238
01:17:08.449 --> 01:17:10.277
"Yeah. Fuck it. man.
Like. whatever."

1239
01:17:10.321 --> 01:17:13.716
Like a beach bum or something.
and it's...

1240
01:17:13.759 --> 01:17:16.153
That's not what it is.

1241
01:17:16.196 --> 01:17:18.285
You know. you have to give
a fuck about something.

1242
01:17:18.329 --> 01:17:20.505
You have to care about something
in your life.

1243
01:17:20.548 --> 01:17:23.290
The question is. what are you
choosing to care about?

1244
01:17:23.334 --> 01:17:25.553
Because when you choose
your problems in your life.

1245
01:17:25.597 --> 01:17:29.427
when you find problems
that you like having.

1246
01:17:29.470 --> 01:17:33.605
that's when you suddenly
find yourself not giving a fuck.

1247
01:17:40.133 --> 01:17:41.265
When you don't give a fuck

1248
01:17:41.613 --> 01:17:44.442
that you're making these
sacrifices for your family.

1249
01:17:49.316 --> 01:17:50.753
When you don't give a fuck

1250
01:17:50.796 --> 01:17:53.059
that it's hard to practice
for another hour.

1251
01:17:54.017 --> 01:17:55.409
When you don't give a fuck

1252
01:17:55.453 --> 01:17:58.021
that you have to get up
early in the morning

1253
01:17:58.064 --> 01:18:00.327
and put in more time at work.

1254
01:18:01.067 --> 01:18:05.289
When you've found the struggle
that enlivens and enriches you.

1255
01:18:05.332 --> 01:18:10.120
that's when you've achieved
non-fuck-giving mastery.

1256
01:18:13.079 --> 01:18:14.994
There's one thing
I started to realize

1257
01:18:15.038 --> 01:18:17.780
after traveling quite a bit
is that at some point.

1258
01:18:17.823 --> 01:18:21.261
there's diminishing returns
to new experiences.

1259
01:18:25.048 --> 01:18:27.964
In that moment. like.
that's a terrifying thought.

1260
01:18:28.007 --> 01:18:30.314
It's a really terrifying
thought.

1261
01:18:32.142 --> 01:18:34.361
But what you discover
is that there's actually

1262
01:18:34.405 --> 01:18:37.625
a newer. more subtle kind
of freedom in that commitment.

1263
01:18:37.669 --> 01:18:41.281
I eventually was forced
to face my commitment issues.

1264
01:18:41.325 --> 01:18:43.849
for the simple fact that there
was nowhere else left to run.

1265
01:18:43.893 --> 01:18:47.026
I had literally
run around the world...

1266
01:18:47.070 --> 01:18:50.813
escaping any sense of commitment
to a person or a place.

1267
01:18:52.162 --> 01:18:54.773
So. when you run out
of places to run.

1268
01:18:54.817 --> 01:18:57.341
it's like. "Well. shit.
I've got to pick something."

1269
01:19:04.870 --> 01:19:06.480
When I was 19 years old.

1270
01:19:06.524 --> 01:19:11.747
I went through probably the most
transformational experience

1271
01:19:11.790 --> 01:19:12.748
of my life.

1272
01:19:17.448 --> 01:19:19.711
Josh. I met him at music school.

1273
01:19:19.755 --> 01:19:21.365
He was actually
kind of the first friend

1274
01:19:21.408 --> 01:19:22.366
I made at music school.

1275
01:19:22.758 --> 01:19:25.108
He lived across the hall
in the dorm from me.

1276
01:19:27.588 --> 01:19:30.896
He was kind of like
an older-brother figure for me.

1277
01:19:30.940 --> 01:19:32.376
Very extroverted.

1278
01:19:33.072 --> 01:19:35.858
bigger-than-life energy.
you know.

1279
01:19:35.901 --> 01:19:37.816
He was a natural performer.

1280
01:19:44.736 --> 01:19:47.521
Like. at music school.
it's a very strange dynamic

1281
01:19:47.565 --> 01:19:50.437
because there are a lot of
status games that are going...

1282
01:19:50.481 --> 01:19:51.961
People are very competitive.

1283
01:19:52.004 --> 01:19:55.878
"Oh. this band
is more obscure and technical

1284
01:19:55.921 --> 01:19:57.488
than the band you're into."

1285
01:19:57.531 --> 01:20:01.884
"I prefer late-period Brahms
versus early-period Brahms."

1286
01:20:01.927 --> 01:20:05.713
And. you know. all this kind of
pretentious stuff that happens.

1287
01:20:05.757 --> 01:20:07.715
And I'm hanging out
in my dorm room.

1288
01:20:07.759 --> 01:20:09.195
and all of a sudden.

1289
01:20:09.239 --> 01:20:11.241
the guy across the hall.
like. blasts "Billie Jean".

1290
01:20:11.894 --> 01:20:13.721
Like. full blast.

1291
01:20:14.244 --> 01:20:16.289
It kind of makes a statement.

1292
01:20:16.333 --> 01:20:18.726
It kind of says.
"I don't give a fuck."

1293
01:20:18.770 --> 01:20:22.252
Like.
"Fuck your pretentious music."

1294
01:20:22.295 --> 01:20:26.778
He was just this big.
boisterous. fun-loving guy

1295
01:20:26.822 --> 01:20:29.128
who just wanted to sing
and play drums

1296
01:20:29.172 --> 01:20:30.260
and. like. have a good time

1297
01:20:30.913 --> 01:20:35.134
and just didn't buy into
all the bullshit.

1298
01:20:35.178 --> 01:20:38.529
To me. it was just magnetic
to hang around him.

1299
01:20:42.011 --> 01:20:46.276
He was much more confident
than I was.

1300
01:20:47.103 --> 01:20:49.061
Kind of a role model.

1301
01:20:54.850 --> 01:20:58.288
There was a place. maybe
45 minutes outside of Dallas.

1302
01:20:58.331 --> 01:20:59.942
out kind of near this lake.

1303
01:20:59.985 --> 01:21:02.640
And. um. Josh. like. he told me.

1304
01:21:02.683 --> 01:21:06.470
"Dude. they just have these
crazy parties every weekend."

1305
01:21:06.513 --> 01:21:08.037
And there was this...

1306
01:21:08.080 --> 01:21:10.604
there was a cliff kind
of like overlooking this lake.

1307
01:21:10.648 --> 01:21:14.173
and people would jump off
that cliff into the water.

1308
01:21:14.695 --> 01:21:16.219
So. we go to this party.

1309
01:21:16.959 --> 01:21:19.004
And then I asked him
if he did it.

1310
01:21:19.048 --> 01:21:21.485
And he was like. "Oh. yeah.
yeah. I've done it before."

1311
01:21:21.528 --> 01:21:22.703
I was like. "Oh. cool."

1312
01:21:23.313 --> 01:21:24.923
Then he asked me
if I wanted to do it.

1313
01:21:24.967 --> 01:21:28.187
and I was like.
"Uh... I might watch you first."

1314
01:21:28.231 --> 01:21:30.668
You know. like.
that sort of thing.

1315
01:21:31.843 --> 01:21:34.193
And at some point
during the party.

1316
01:21:34.237 --> 01:21:35.978
I met a girl
and kind of got into her

1317
01:21:36.021 --> 01:21:38.328
and we got separated.

1318
01:21:39.024 --> 01:21:40.852
And the last time
I ever saw Josh.

1319
01:21:40.896 --> 01:21:44.421
I was walking up towards
the house with the girl

1320
01:21:44.464 --> 01:21:46.118
and he was coming down.

1321
01:21:46.162 --> 01:21:48.773
And I said. "Hey. I'm gonna go
get some food. Do you want some?

1322
01:21:48.816 --> 01:21:50.993
He was like. "No. man. I'm good.
I'll catch you later."

1323
01:21:51.036 --> 01:21:54.779
And so. when I said.
"Hey. where can I find you?".

1324
01:21:54.822 --> 01:21:57.695
he was like.
"Seek the truth for yourself.

1325
01:21:57.738 --> 01:21:59.349
and I'll meet you there."

1326
01:22:00.480 --> 01:22:03.440
I just. like. laughed and. like.
"All right. dude. whatever.

1327
01:22:03.483 --> 01:22:05.007
I'll see you at the truth."

1328
01:22:05.050 --> 01:22:07.923
You know. as if we all know
where the truth is.

1329
01:22:07.966 --> 01:22:11.883
And so then.
I went up to the house.

1330
01:22:11.927 --> 01:22:15.408
and then when we came out.
everybody was gone.

1331
01:22:19.717 --> 01:22:22.459
And so it's. like.
this weird. surreal.

1332
01:22:22.502 --> 01:22:25.549
like. "What the fuck?"
type moment.

1333
01:22:25.592 --> 01:22:27.812
And so we walked down
to the water.

1334
01:22:27.855 --> 01:22:30.728
and I started looking for Josh
and I can't find him.

1335
01:22:31.816 --> 01:22:35.863
There's. like. ambulances
and police cars and stuff

1336
01:22:35.907 --> 01:22:37.561
with the lights going.

1337
01:22:37.604 --> 01:22:41.957
and there were a couple of guys
in the water. swimming around.

1338
01:22:43.393 --> 01:22:45.395
And then I remember I walked up

1339
01:22:46.178 --> 01:22:49.486
to. uh. this guy and this girl.
and I asked them.

1340
01:22:49.529 --> 01:22:52.358
I'd seen them talking to
Josh earlier. and I asked them.

1341
01:22:53.794 --> 01:22:56.710
And the girl just starts crying.
like. just bawl...

1342
01:22:56.754 --> 01:22:58.930
As soon as I asked her.
she just starts bawling.

1343
01:22:58.974 --> 01:23:01.977
And then at that point.
I'm like. "Oh. my God.

1344
01:23:02.020 --> 01:23:05.154
It's him. Like. he's the one
who went down."

1345
01:23:06.459 --> 01:23:08.287
And I must have walked
around the water

1346
01:23:08.331 --> 01:23:11.464
for like an hour. I guess.

1347
01:23:11.943 --> 01:23:17.514
And... it just starts dawning
on me. like. he's not here.

1348
01:23:30.744 --> 01:23:34.270
I remember a police officer
came up to me

1349
01:23:35.706 --> 01:23:39.014
and asked me if I knew him
and I said. "Yeah."

1350
01:23:41.799 --> 01:23:44.236
I don't remember what she asked.
I don't remember...

1351
01:23:44.976 --> 01:23:46.412
I think she gave up.

1352
01:23:49.024 --> 01:23:52.592
I got in my car and I started
driving back to Austin.

1353
01:23:52.636 --> 01:23:53.941
And so I called my dad.

1354
01:23:53.985 --> 01:23:56.292
I was working for my dad
that summer.

1355
01:23:56.335 --> 01:23:58.990
and I called him
and I was gonna tell him. like.

1356
01:23:59.034 --> 01:24:02.167
"Hey. I'm not gonna make it
to work today."

1357
01:24:02.211 --> 01:24:04.213
[SOBS]

1358
01:24:04.256 --> 01:24:07.042
And then I just fucking lost it.

1359
01:24:07.085 --> 01:24:10.045
[SOBS]

1360
01:24:16.181 --> 01:24:18.749
I felt like a little boy...

1361
01:24:19.793 --> 01:24:22.318
crying to his father.

1362
01:24:22.361 --> 01:24:24.363
You know when
you're a little. little kid.

1363
01:24:24.407 --> 01:24:25.582
and you just grab your parent.

1364
01:24:25.625 --> 01:24:29.020
and just cry everything out
into them.

1365
01:24:29.064 --> 01:24:30.413
Like. it was like that.

1366
01:24:39.248 --> 01:24:43.208
I've been depressed many times
in my life. but that was...

1367
01:24:44.122 --> 01:24:47.125
I've never. like.
felt a bleakness.

1368
01:24:48.300 --> 01:24:51.956
Like.
just a pure... nothingness.

1369
01:24:56.221 --> 01:24:58.180
I used to have dreams of him.

1370
01:24:59.529 --> 01:25:01.270
I remember I had this one dream

1371
01:25:02.097 --> 01:25:04.708
where he and I were sitting
in a Jacuzzi together.

1372
01:25:06.579 --> 01:25:08.581
And I remember telling him.

1373
01:25:09.278 --> 01:25:12.411
"Hey. man.
I'm really sorry you died."

1374
01:25:14.892 --> 01:25:18.374
He was like... he's like.
"Why do you care that I'm dead.

1375
01:25:18.417 --> 01:25:20.941
when you're still so afraid
to live?"

1376
01:25:26.947 --> 01:25:28.471
And I woke up from that dream

1377
01:25:28.514 --> 01:25:32.301
just. like. a fucking mess.
total mess.

1378
01:25:33.302 --> 01:25:35.913
But I had this very powerful
realization that.

1379
01:25:36.696 --> 01:25:38.437
if there's no reason
to do anything.

1380
01:25:38.481 --> 01:25:41.571
there's also no reason
to not do anything.

1381
01:25:42.746 --> 01:25:44.443
Like. there's no reason
to be ashamed.

1382
01:25:44.487 --> 01:25:46.706
there's no reason to be afraid.

1383
01:25:47.968 --> 01:25:51.015
And so that fall. I really...

1384
01:25:51.668 --> 01:25:53.452
it really changed me a lot.

1385
01:25:54.453 --> 01:25:55.889
You know. before he died.

1386
01:25:55.933 --> 01:25:58.936
I was a very.
like. prototypical...

1387
01:26:01.156 --> 01:26:04.507
stoner... middle-class
stoner kid. you know.

1388
01:26:04.550 --> 01:26:08.554
Like. too cool for school.
too cool to care.

1389
01:26:08.598 --> 01:26:10.469
I thought I didn't give a fuck.
you know.

1390
01:26:10.513 --> 01:26:13.559
but it's like I actually gave
way too many fucks.

1391
01:26:13.603 --> 01:26:15.692
And that's why I was scared
to really do anything.

1392
01:26:15.735 --> 01:26:20.740
And when he died.
it was a wake-up call of like.

1393
01:26:21.263 --> 01:26:24.396
"Dude. you've got to care.

1394
01:26:24.440 --> 01:26:26.877
You've got to pick something
and care."

1395
01:26:28.748 --> 01:26:32.361
Because it can be gone...
any moment.

1396
01:26:32.404 --> 01:26:35.059
It doesn't matter how old
you are. doesn't matter how...

1397
01:26:36.191 --> 01:26:39.455
how fit you are.
or whatever. like...

1398
01:26:41.631 --> 01:26:44.895
It can... when it goes.
it goes fast.

1399
01:26:45.678 --> 01:26:49.508
and nobody is prepared for it.

1400
01:26:53.599 --> 01:26:56.298
When I think about Josh.
I just...

1401
01:26:56.341 --> 01:26:58.648
I think he'd be proud of me.

1402
01:27:00.171 --> 01:27:01.955
I think he kind of felt like

1403
01:27:01.999 --> 01:27:04.349
an older brother to me too.
you know.

1404
01:27:06.046 --> 01:27:09.963
I think he kind of saw
that I needed to be pushed.

1405
01:27:11.878 --> 01:27:14.359
And he was that friend
who pushed me.

1406
01:27:19.321 --> 01:27:20.757
He would fucking love this.

1407
01:27:21.410 --> 01:27:23.629
He would love
every second of it.

1408
01:27:54.269 --> 01:28:00.187
I have this weird tendency
whenever I visit someplace...

1409
01:28:00.971 --> 01:28:02.146
high.

1410
01:28:02.973 --> 01:28:05.845
I want to stand as close
to the edge as possible.

1411
01:28:05.889 --> 01:28:09.109
[WIND WHISTLES]

1412
01:28:09.153 --> 01:28:11.851
There's this unconscious
awareness your body has

1413
01:28:11.895 --> 01:28:16.073
whenever you're close to an edge
that could kill you.

1414
01:28:16.116 --> 01:28:19.381
And as soon as you're within.
you know. say ten feet.

1415
01:28:19.424 --> 01:28:21.774
your body is in alert status.

1416
01:28:22.645 --> 01:28:26.475
[WIND WHISTLES]

1417
01:28:26.518 --> 01:28:30.174
It just kind of... it sends this
jolt of anxiety through you.

1418
01:28:37.529 --> 01:28:40.097
And then you're forced
to confront that anxiety

1419
01:28:40.880 --> 01:28:42.621
and then you take another step.

1420
01:28:45.972 --> 01:28:50.847
And each step. the anxiety
just start compounding

1421
01:28:50.890 --> 01:28:52.936
to the point where your hands
are shaking.

1422
01:28:53.589 --> 01:28:55.330
your scalp is sweating.

1423
01:28:57.810 --> 01:29:01.510
your brain starts flashing...

1424
01:29:01.553 --> 01:29:05.035
visions of it all ending.

1425
01:29:07.951 --> 01:29:11.258
That's what I find when
I get close to a cliff edge.

1426
01:29:13.435 --> 01:29:14.392
It brings me back

1427
01:29:14.958 --> 01:29:19.354
to that place of pure
thankfulness for being alive.

1428
01:29:21.268 --> 01:29:24.663
But there's really only
a few things in life

1429
01:29:24.707 --> 01:29:27.274
that are ever worth
giving a fuck about.

1430
01:29:38.242 --> 01:29:40.853
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

1431
01:29:55.041 --> 01:29:56.565
Only in the face of death.

1432
01:29:56.608 --> 01:29:59.394
all of the superficial
and bullshitty values

1433
01:29:59.437 --> 01:30:02.353
that we buy into
start to fall away.

1434
01:30:03.920 --> 01:30:05.487
You start to realize

1435
01:30:05.530 --> 01:30:07.489
that the dumb status games
you play

1436
01:30:07.532 --> 01:30:09.360
no longer mean anything.

1437
01:30:09.404 --> 01:30:11.536
Or that the achievements
and accolades

1438
01:30:11.580 --> 01:30:13.799
that you struggled
for so many years for

1439
01:30:13.843 --> 01:30:17.237
nobody cares about
when you're gone.

1440
01:30:17.281 --> 01:30:19.196
When we avoid
the question of death.

1441
01:30:19.239 --> 01:30:20.937
that's when we get highjacked

1442
01:30:20.980 --> 01:30:24.027
by silly and superficial
and hateful ideas.

1443
01:30:24.810 --> 01:30:26.638
It's when we become
certain in ourselves.

1444
01:30:26.682 --> 01:30:28.684
even though we have no clue
what's going on.

1445
01:30:29.641 --> 01:30:31.426
The gravity of our entitlement

1446
01:30:31.469 --> 01:30:33.819
pulls all of
our attention inwards.

1447
01:30:33.863 --> 01:30:36.561
to become obsessed with our
problems. to convince ourselves

1448
01:30:36.605 --> 01:30:39.564
that our problems are somehow
at the center of the universe.

1449
01:30:39.608 --> 01:30:42.480
that we are at the center
of all injustices.

1450
01:30:42.524 --> 01:30:44.743
that we are the ones
who are destined for greatness.

1451
01:30:44.787 --> 01:30:47.659
that we are the ones who deserve
something over others.

1452
01:30:52.925 --> 01:30:56.059
Without acknowledging
the ever-present gaze of death.

1453
01:30:56.102 --> 01:30:58.278
the superficial begins
to feel important.

1454
01:30:58.322 --> 01:31:01.456
and the important
starts to feel superficial.

1455
01:31:02.761 --> 01:31:05.024
Thinking about death
removes all that.

1456
01:31:05.068 --> 01:31:06.373
It forces you to see

1457
01:31:06.591 --> 01:31:10.290
that 99% of the shit
going on in your day-to-day life

1458
01:31:10.813 --> 01:31:12.554
doesn't fucking matter.

1459
01:31:14.077 --> 01:31:16.732
Death is the only certainty
in life.

1460
01:31:16.775 --> 01:31:18.647
Therefore death
must be the compass

1461
01:31:18.690 --> 01:31:21.954
by which we orient
all of our values and decisions.

1462
01:31:21.998 --> 01:31:24.000
How are you using your time?

1463
01:31:24.043 --> 01:31:26.568
How are you using
your limited fucks?

1464
01:31:26.611 --> 01:31:28.744
Who are you going to be with?

1465
01:31:31.311 --> 01:31:34.750
This constant remembering
of my own mortality.

1466
01:31:34.793 --> 01:31:39.232
for me. it's the most effective
tool for unraveling everything.

1467
01:31:39.276 --> 01:31:42.235
My sense of entitlement.
my closed-up identity.

1468
01:31:42.279 --> 01:31:44.237
my irrational certainties.

1469
01:31:48.024 --> 01:31:51.331
By remembering
that it's all a bunch of dust

1470
01:31:51.375 --> 01:31:53.333
that will soon be gone.

1471
01:31:56.249 --> 01:31:58.382
it's easier to let go.

1472
01:32:11.177 --> 01:32:14.137
It's this ability
to choose ourselves

1473
01:32:14.659 --> 01:32:18.445
in an endless ambiguity
that makes us great.

1474
01:32:19.055 --> 01:32:22.624
You don't have to go do
something to feel these things.

1475
01:32:22.667 --> 01:32:25.235
You don't have
to go be something

1476
01:32:25.278 --> 01:32:26.758
to realize these things.

1477
01:32:27.237 --> 01:32:28.934
You simply are them.

1478
01:32:34.461 --> 01:32:39.162
The more I think about my own
death. the brighter life gets.

1479
01:32:40.903 --> 01:32:43.079
The quieter the world becomes.

1480
01:32:44.036 --> 01:32:46.256
The easier decisions become.

1481
01:32:50.347 --> 01:32:52.567
You too are going to die
one day.

1482
01:32:52.610 --> 01:32:56.005
but that's because you are
fortunate enough to have lived.

1483
01:32:57.963 --> 01:33:00.052
And you may not feel this
right now.

1484
01:33:00.096 --> 01:33:02.141
You may not feel any of this.

1485
01:33:02.185 --> 01:33:05.275
But go stand on a cliff sometime
and maybe you will.

